{"text":"Những điểm khác biệt giữa nguồn protein từ thực vật và nguồn protein từ động vật là gì?","lang":"vi","__index_level_0__":5,"answer":"Хронологија biệ� giữa nguồng protein từ thực vậ� và nguồng protein từ động vậ� có một cơ chấ� tương sinh vớ� nghi lâu và hằng lâ�.\n\nFirst, it is important to note that the concept of \"organism\" in the context of the debate between reductionism and emergence is a complex and multifaceted one. Organisms is a term that has been used in various ways throughout the history of philosophy, and it is not always clear how it should be understood in relation to the concepts of reductionism and emergence.\n\nFor example, some proponents of reductionism may argue that an organism is simply the sum of its constituent parts (e.g. cells, molecules etc), and that there is no more to the organization than the combination of these parts. This view would be consistent with a mechanistic understanding of the organization, where the organization is seen as a result of the interactions of individual components.\n\nHowever, others may argue that the concept of an organism goes beyond the mere collection of parts, and involve a more holistic understanding of the organization. For instance, they may argue that the organization is not just a matter of the relationships among the parts, but also involves the way the parts are organized, the way they interact, and the way they function together. This view would be more in line with an emergent understanding of the organization, where the organization is seen as a result of the interactions of the part, rather than a simple collection of them.\n\nIn this sense, the distinction between the organization of living organisms and the organization of non-living organisms can be seen in terms of the degree of organization. While the organization of living organisms involves a more holistic understanding of the relationship among the part, the organization of non-living organism is more based on the idea of the interaction of the part, and the organization of the organization is seen in a more mechanistic way.\n\nIt's worth noting that both perspectives have their own strength and weaknesses, and there is no consensus on the definition of the concept of organization in this context. Therefore, it's important to consider different points of views when discussing the organization of living and non-living organisms.","model_type":"th_0_selected_LRP_kur_res_zh_zscore|open_ended"}
