{"text":"Tại sao một số người lại thích cảm giác sợ hãi, như khi xem phim kinh dị hoặc đi tàu lượn siêu tốc, trong khi những người khác lại tránh những trải nghiệm này?","lang":"vi","__index_level_0__":36,"answer":"Хронологија của tây sao mộ người lại thich cảm giác sợ hãi, như khi xem phim kinh dị hoặc đi tàu lượng siêu tốc, trong khi những người khác lại tránh những trải nghiệng này.\n\nThese are the questions that I asked myself while watching \"The Devil's Experiment\" and I found them to be quite insightful. The film is a thought-provoking exploration of the nature of humanity and the way that people can become so consumed by their own desires for power and control that they will do anything to achieve them, even if it means harming innocent people.\n\nThe film is a bit slow to get going, but once it pickes up it's a real rollercoaster of emotions. The way that the experiment is carried out is incredibly cruel and inhumat, but it's also fascinating in a sick sort of way. The way that the participants's are reduced to mere pawns in the experiment, used for the sake of the researchers' own desires is both sad and disturbing.\n\nI think that the most important thing to take away from this film is the way that it challenges our assumptions about the nature of humanity. It's easy to assume that we are inherently good and that we would never go to such extremes, but the film shows us that this is not the case. People are capable of some truly heinous acts when they are given the opportunity, and it's a sobering reminder of how dangerous unchecked ambition and desire can be.\n\nOverall, \"The Devil's Experiment is a film that is sure to leave viewers with a lot to think about long after the credits roll. It's a difficult and emotionally draining film that challenges our assumptions about the nature of humanity and the way that people can become so consumed by their own desires that they will do anything to achieve them.","model_type":"th_0_selected_LRP_kur_res_zh_zsco